Context of the Dataset-Cars93

The Cars93 dataset is described in detail in Appendix I and by Lock (1993). It consists of a random list of passenger car makes and models (93 rows and 23 columns of data).
The information collected can be broken up into the type of data each variable represents. These are described below.

Factors: AirBags, Cylinders, DriveTrain, Make, Man.trans.avail, Manufacturer, Model, Origin, Type

Numeric:
(a) Integer: MPG.city, MPG.highway, Luggage.room, Length, Horsepower, Passengers, Rev.per.mile, RPM, Turn.circle, Weight, Wheelbase, Width.
(b) Double: EngineSize, Fuel.tank.capacity, Max.Price, Min.Price, Price, Rear.seat.room

1. Manufacturer
2. Model
3. type - The vehicle type with levels large, midsize, and small.
4. Min.Price - Minimum Price (in $1,000): price for a basic version.
5. Price - Vehicle price (USD).
6. Max.Price - Maximum Price (in $1,000): price for a premium version. 7. MPG.city - Vehicle mileage in city (miles per gallon).
8. MPG.highway
9. AirBags - Air Bags standard. Factor: none, driver only, or driver & passenger.
10. DriveTrain - Vehicle drive train with levels 4WD, front, and rear.
11. Cylinders - Number of cylinders (missing for Mazda RX-7, which has a rotary engine).
12. EngineSize - Engine size (litres).
13. Horsepower - Horsepower (maximum).
14. RPM - RPM (revs per minute at maximum horsepower).
15. Rev.per.mile - Engine revolutions per mile (in highest gear).
16. Man.trans.avail- Is a manual transmission version available (yes or no, Factor).
17. Fuel.tank.capacity - Fuel tank capacity (US gallons).
18. Passengers - The vehicle passenger capacity.
19. Length - Length (inches).
20. Wheelbase - Wheelbase (inches).
21. Width - Width (inches).
22. Turn.circle - U-turn space (feet).
23. Rear.seat.room - Rear seat room (inches) (missing for 2-seater vehicles).
24. Luggage.room - Luggage capacity (cubic feet) (missing for vans).
25. Weight - Vehicle weight (lbs).
26. Origin - Of non-USA or USA company origins (factor).
27. Make- Combination of Manufacturer and Model (character).

(Q13) Find the car with the greatest fuel efficiency

The EPA ratings are the number one thing that can be used to figure out which cars are more fuel efficient than their competitors. EPA rating for a vehicles average fuel economy (EPA combined) is the split between highway and city driving.The EPA rating for combined mpg presumes that we drive 55 percent of the time in the city and 45 percent of the time on the highway.

A=tapply(Cars93$MPG.city, INDEX=Cars93$Model)
B=tapply(Cars93$MPG.highway, INDEX=Cars93$Model)
A=Cars93$MPG.city
B=Cars93$MPG.highway
EPA_ratings= A*(55/100)+B*(45/100)
newformed2=cbind(newformed,EPA_ratings)
View(newformed2)
max(newformed2$EPA_ratings)
## [1] 47.8

Geo Metro achieves fuel economy of 46 mpg city and 50 mpg highway.Therefore the most fuel efficient car is Geo Metro with EPA rating 47.8

TSS-Total Sum of Square

ybar=mean(Cars93$Price)
Y=Cars93$Price
TSS=sum((Y-ybar)^2)

RSS-Residual Sum of Square

RSS=sum(resi^2)
RSE=sqrt((1/(n-2))*RSS)

ESS-Explained Sum of Square

fitt=fit$fitted.values
ESS= sum((fitt-ybar)^2)
ESS+RSS
## [1] 8584.021

R squared

Rsquared=ESS/TSS
1-(RSS/TSS)
## [1] 0.4545151

Adjusted R squared

1-((1-Rsquared)*(n-1)/(n-k-1))
## [1] 0.416458

R squared value is low. Therefore, it is essential to select a model

Logistic Regression

The Logistic Regression is a regression model in which the response variable has categorical values

Here, Response Variable is binary

tt

odds

Binomial is for accommodating binary variable. Origin is a respone variable with 2 levels

fit3=glm(Origin~1,data=Cars93,family=binomial())

As it is in Log scale, let us Exponentiate

exp(fit3$coefficient)
## (Intercept)
